1667

METHOD 3 : USING STORED PROCEDURE


DELIMITER //
CREATE PROCEDURE FixNames()
BEGIN
    UPDATE Users
    SET name = CONCAT(UPPER(SUBSTRING(name, 1, 1)), LOWER(SUBSTRING(name, 2)));
END //
DELIMITER ;
CALL FixNames();


Explanation:
â€¢	This solution uses a stored procedure in MySQL to fix the capitalization of names in the Users table, ensuring that only the first letter is uppercase and the rest are lowercase.
â€¢	DELIMITER //:Changes the delimiter from the default semicolon (;) to // so that you can use semicolons inside the procedure without terminating it prematurely.
â€¢	CREATE PROCEDURE FixNames():Defines a stored procedure called FixNames().
â€¢	BEGIN ... END:Marks the beginning and end of the procedure body.
â€¢	UPDATE Users SET name = CONCAT(UPPER(SUBSTRING(name, 1, 1)), LOWER(SUBSTRING(name, 2)));:This SQL statement updates the name column in the Users table. It does the following:
â€¢	SUBSTRING(name, 1, 1): Extracts the first character of the name.
â€¢	UPPER(SUBSTRING(name, 1, 1)): Converts the first character to uppercase.
â€¢	SUBSTRING(name, 2): Extracts the rest of the string (from the second character onward).
â€¢	LOWER(SUBSTRING(name, 2)): Converts the rest of the string to lowercase.
â€¢	CONCAT(...): Combines the uppercase first letter with the lowercase remainder of the name.
â€¢	DELIMITER ;:Resets the delimiter back to semicolon (;).
â€¢	CALL FixNames();:Calls the stored procedure FixNames() to execute the UPDATE query and fix all the names in the Users table.
â€¢	Once the stored procedure is executed, all the names in the Users table will be updated so that only the first character is uppercase and the rest are lowercase.
